Here's the approach:

### 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Create matching `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` with different color values using the **same keys**.

### 2. Add a theme-switching helper

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeManager
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        mergedDicts.Clear();

        mergedDicts.Add(theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new LightTheme()
        });

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

### 3. Apply the saved theme at startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeManager.LoadSavedTheme();
}
```

### 4. Wire up the settings page

```xml
<Picker Title="Theme" SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (sender is Picker p && Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(p.SelectedItem?.ToString(), out var theme))
        ThemeManager.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

### 5. Consume theme colors in your pages

Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) so values update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" Text="Hello!" />
</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**

- **`DynamicResource`** is essential — it re-evaluates when the dictionary changes.
- **`MergedDictionaries.Clear()` + `Add()`** swaps the active theme instantly.
- **`Preferences`** persists the choice across app restarts.
- Keep the same `x:Key` names across all three dictionaries so every binding resolves regardless of theme.
